Browser â†’ Server:
â€œHi, send me your TLS certificate.â€

Server sends certificate, containing:

domain name (must match)

public key

certificate authority signature (CA)

Browser verifies certificate

Is this domain valid?

Is it signed by a trusted authority?

If valid:

Browser creates a random secret key â†’ encrypts it with serverâ€™s public key â†’ sends it to server.

Server decrypts using its private key.

Now both have the same secret key â†’ use it to encrypt all communication.

This is known as TLS handshake.

ğŸ”’ 3. Does HTTPS Mean End-to-End Encryption?

Not exactly.

